---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const promptText = `# IconTree Integration

Integrate IconTree Lottie icons into an existing app. Do not scaffold a new app, icon library, gallery, marketplace, search page, or design system.

Step 0 — Pick your path

| Project type | Path |
|---|---|
| React (web) | Use the icon-tree-animate npm package — Path A. Skip Path B entirely. |
| Flutter / React Native / Android / other | Use the generic API workflow — Path B. |

Path A — React: icon-tree-animate package

Install

Peer deps: react + react-dom (>=18).

\`\`\`
npm install icon-tree-animate
\`\`\`

Add icons (CLI, design-time only)

This searches the IconTree API, saves JSON to \`src/icons/<iconId>.json\`, and regenerates \`src/registry.ts\`. Run it once per icon at design time — never at runtime.

\`\`\`
npx icontree add <iconId> --search "<query>"
npx icontree add heart --search "heart"
npx icontree add arrow-right --search "arrow right" --interactive
# pick from multiple results
\`\`\`

Use the component

\`\`\`tsx
import { Icon } from "icon-tree-animate";

<Icon id="heart" size={48} color="#ff0000" mode="static" />
<Icon id="heart" size={48} color="#00ff00" mode="loop" />
<Icon id="heart" size={48} color="#0000ff" mode="onClick" onClick={() => handleClick()} />
<Icon id="heart" size={48} color="#ffaa00" mode="hover" />
\`\`\`

Props

| Prop | Type | Default | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| id | IconId | required | must exist in registry |
| size | number \\| string | 24 | width/height |
| color | string | "currentColor" | hex, e.g. "#ff0000" |
| mode | "static"\\|"loop"\\|"onClick"\\|"hover" | "static" | see below |
| onClick | () => void | — | fires in onClick mode |
| resetAfterPlay | boolean | true | reset to frame 0 after playing |
| className | string | — | |
| style | React.CSSProperties | — | |

Modes: \`static\` = frame 0 only, no animation · \`loop\` = autoplay, infinite · \`onClick\` = idle at frame 0, plays once on click · \`hover\` = idle at frame 0, plays once on mouse-enter, finishes on mouse-leave.

How it works

Design-time (CLI): add-icon.js fetches raw Lottie JSON, saves to \`src/icons/\`, no color applied.
Runtime (component): icon JSON loaded via dynamic import (tree-shakeable), recolored in-memory from the \`color\` prop, rendered via Lottie. Zero network requests. \`recolorLottie()\` deep-clones the JSON, converts hex → Lottie RGBA floats, walks the layer tree updating fill/stroke, and memoizes by icon+color.

Integration rules

Wire \`<Icon />\` into existing components only; reuse existing spacing/colors/theme/naming.
\`color\` prop should read from the app's theme tokens (light/dark), not hardcoded hex, unless the project already hardcodes colors elsewhere.
Output only the required code — no README, no extra files, no console logs.
If the user explicitly wants an in-app icon picker/search UI, pause and confirm — that's a different feature from this integration and needs the search API shipped client-side (normally out of scope).

Path B — Non-React (Flutter / React Native / Android / other)

Target (fill in)

Framework: [Flutter / React Native / Android / etc.]
Component: [component name]
Lottie library: [lottie_flutter, lottie-react-native, lottie-android, etc.]
Local icon path: [e.g. assets/icons]

Ground rules

Integrate into existing UI only — no new icon library/gallery/marketplace/search page/design system.
Reuse existing components, spacing, colors, theme, naming.
Output only required code — no README, boilerplate, explanations, unrelated files, console/print logs.
IconTree provides only Lottie .json — never SVG.

Design-time icon selection (AI performs this, not the app)

Base URL: https://icontree.cosmoscope.workers.dev

Search:
\`\`\`
GET /icon/search?q=<query>&category=<optional>&page=<optional>&pageSize=<optional>
→ { "results": [ { "url": "/path/icon.json" } ] }
\`\`\`

Workflow: search → pick best match → download (see Theming below) → bundle JSON as a local asset → final code references the local asset only, never the live URL. Never ship search/fetch calls inside the app. If the user wants an in-app picker/search UI, confirm first — separate feature.

Runtime (production)

Import the local JSON, render with the project's existing Lottie library, no network requests, no dynamic fetching.

Theming / icon color

IconTree JSON ships with a fixed baked-in fill (often white/black) that won't match app theme. Two options:

1. Server-side recolor (recommended) — at design time, download the pre-colored variant instead of the raw icon:
   \`\`\`
   GET {baseUrl}/icon/use/<iconname>.json?color=<hex>
   e.g. /icon/use/arrow-right-bold.json?color=ff0000
   \`\`\`
   Leading # optional (ff0000 or %23ff0000 both work). Bundle the returned JSON directly — no runtime color code needed. For light/dark support, download + bundle one colored JSON per theme (e.g. \`icon-name.light.json\` / \`icon-name.dark.json\`) and switch assets on active theme.

2. Runtime recolor — only if the app must recolor dynamically without a rebuild: use the platform Lottie library's native color-override mechanism (dynamic properties, color filters, or JSON preprocessing that swaps fill/stroke). Prefer option 1 otherwise.

Component requirements

Follow existing project architecture/patterns.
Keep size, loop, autoplay, etc. configurable via props/params unless the project already hardcodes equivalents.
Proper typing (TS/Dart/etc. as applicable).
Production-ready code, no TODOs/placeholders/console logs.`;
---

<Layout title="IconTree - AI Prompt">
  <div class="doc-content doc-content-wide prompt-shell">
    <div class="doc-nav">
      <a href="/" class="back-link">&lt; Back</a>
    </div>

    <section class="doc-hero">
      <span class="doc-kicker">AI Prompt</span>
      <h1>One Prompt to Use IconTree</h1>
      <p class="doc-lead">
        This prompt is for adding IconTree icons into an existing app, not for building a new icon library.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="prompt-card">
      <h3>Prompt</h3>
      <p>Copy this prompt into your AI tool when you want it to build or integrate IconTree correctly.</p>
      <pre><code>{promptText}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="lang-grid" aria-label="Prompt guidance">
      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The prompt tells the AI three things clearly: use the existing app, choose API or manual mode, and only
          write integration code for that app feature.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>How to Add It</h3>
        <p>
          Paste the prompt first, then add one short line about your stack and target screen, like "Use React on the
          settings page" or "Use Android Kotlin in the onboarding screen".
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-callout">
      <p><strong>Example add-on lines</strong></p>
      <ul class="prompt-list">
        <li><code>Use React and Tailwind.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use Android Kotlin with a LottieAnimationView.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use manual local JSON files, not remote API calls.</code></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script>
    (function() {
      const preBlocks = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.doc-content pre')) as HTMLElement[];

      preBlocks.forEach((pre: HTMLElement) => {
        const btn = document.createElement('button');
        btn.className = 'copy-snippet-btn';
        btn.textContent = 'Copy';
        btn.type = 'button';
        pre.style.position = 'relative';
        pre.appendChild(btn);

        btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const code = pre.querySelector('code');
          const text = code?.textContent || '';

          navigator.clipboard.writeText(text).then(() => {
            btn.textContent = 'Copied!';
            btn.classList.add('copied');

            setTimeout(() => {
              btn.textContent = 'Copy';
              btn.classList.remove('copied');
            }, 2000);
          });
        });
      });
    })();
  </script>
</Layout>
